<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-470-138  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 470 138.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  May 9 1990 n132 p23(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Police raid BBS operation. (West Midlands bulletin board operationsuspected of defrauding British Telecom)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (cases).andO;Topic:     Computer Bulletin BoardsFraudTelephone SystemsLegal IssuesComputer CrimesFederation Against Software Theft.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Police raid BBS operation A West Midlands bulletin board operation has beenraided by the police, following allegations received by FAST (FederationAgainst Software Theft) that it has been using 'black boxes' to defraudBritish Telecom of telephone charge revenue.andM;Detective Chief Inspector Paine of Number Five Regional Crime Squad confirmedthat following raids on a number of addresses around the country, 13individuals were arrested and quantities of hardware and 'black boxes'seized, together with around 25,000 pounds of pirated leisure and businesssoftware.andM;&quot;The allegations involve the use of meter suppression devices, commonlyreferred to as 'black boxes', to defraud BT, and are believed to involvecomputer bulletin board activities.andP;  The equipment seized is now beingexamined,&quot; said Paine.andP;  &quot;The individuals involved have been questioned andreleased on police bail, awaiting decision results.&quot;andM;Bob Hay, Chief Executive of FAST, believes that this is the first time actionhas been taken regarding illegal bulletin board activities in the UK.andP;  &quot;Mostbulletin boards are perfectly lawful and serve a useful purpose, but the manyopportunities open for illegal practices are very worrying,&quot; he commented.andM;This was backed up by a spokesman for ELSPA (European Leisure SoftwarePublishers Association).andP;  &quot;Bulletin boards are fine if they are managedproperly.andP;  If uncontrolled, however, they pose a real threat to law and orderand should carry the strongest penalties for misuse,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>